The appendix, in its present form, is notan enlargement oi the former one, but has been written independently. It is intended primarily to gatherinto a systematic whole the grammatical notes given in the Iessons, and to supplement them; and it is furthermore intended to include all the grammatical material which need be put into the hands oi a Caesar or Cicero class. The regular paradigma are given in full, with only such · exceptional forms as are needed fer the reading of Caesar and Cicero, It is believed that the treatment of syntax covers all the essential usages of those authore, and that the relatively large amount of explanation is given only where it is needed. Rules are almost invariably stated in full, so that when the student takes up a more complete grammar he will have to master only the exceptions, not the principles.

The examples are in part made up, for the sake of brevity and clear- ness, but are drawn largely from Caesar and Cicero¹ References to Caesar are made by book, chapter, and line of the chapter as nearly as the varying editions will permit. References to Cicero are made by oration and scetiorr.

The writer has consulted the usual authorities and is under special obligations, as regards the treatment of the verb, to the writings and personal instruction of Professor William Gardner Halc. The present treatment of the verbis by no means in full accord with Professor Hale’s, yet it is largely influenced by it.
